Uncomplicated Firewall (UFW) is a Linux application that manages netfilter firewalls using a command-line interface (CLI).           



How to configure a Firewall:
            
            sudo apt install ufw  - To install the ufw firewall.             

            sudo ufw app list   - List of applications that allows firewall services.

            sudo ufw status    -  To know the status of the firewall (Status: inactive, active)

            sudo ufw enable    -  To enable the firewall

            sudo ufw status verbose  - To show the firewall rules

            sudo ufw allow 80/tcp   -  To allow tcp(port 80) services
            
            sudo ufw status numbered  - To show the firewall rules number-wise( To show the Firewall-list)

            sudo ufw allow 21:100/tcp (range from 21 to 100) - To allow the range of services  

            sudo ufw allow from 192.168.1.1 (IP Address)    -  To allow certain ip address by firewall

            sudo ufw allow deny 192.168.1.1 (IP Address)    -  To deny certain ip address by firewall

            sudo ufw delete Number(Eg:4)-  To delete a certain rule of firewall from the firewall list


Basic Commands for firewalld:-
     Check Firewall Status: sudo firewall-cmd --state (or sudo systemctl status firewalld) 
     Start firewalld: sudo systemctl start firewalld 
      Enable firewalld on boot: sudo systemctl enable firewalld 
     List Zones: sudo firewall-cmd --get-zones 
     List Active Zones: sudo firewall-cmd --get-active-zones 
     List Services: sudo firewall-cmd --get-services 
     Add a service (runtime): sudo firewall-cmd --add-service=<service_name> (e.g., sudo firewall-cmd --add-service=http) 
     Add a service (permanent): sudo firewall-cmd --permanent --add-service=<service_name> 
     Remove a service (runtime): sudo firewall-cmd --remove-service=<service_name> 
     Remove a service (permanent): sudo firewall-cmd --permanent --remove-service=<service_name> 
     Add a port (runtime): sudo firewall-cmd --add-port=<port_number>/<protocol> (e.g., sudo firewall-cmd --add-port=8080/tcp) 
     Add a port (permanent): sudo firewall-cmd --permanent --add-port=<port_number>/<protocol> 
     Remove a port (runtime): sudo firewall-cmd --remove-port=<port_number>/<protocol> 
     Remove a port (permanent): sudo firewall-cmd --permanent --remove-port=<port_number>/<protocol> 
     Reload Firewall: sudo firewall-cmd --reload (required to apply permanent changes) 
     Get Default Zone: sudo firewall-cmd --get-default-zone 
     Set Default Zone: sudo firewall-cmd --set-default-zone=<zone_name> 
     List Rich Rules: sudo firewall-cmd --list-rich-rules
     Examples
     To allow SSH traffic permanently: sudo firewall-cmd --permanent --add-service=ssh 
     To open port 80 (HTTP) permanently: sudo firewall-cmd --permanent --add-port=80/tcp 
     To allow access to a specific IP address (runtime): sudo firewall-cmd --add-rich-rule='rule family="ipv4" source address="192.168.1.100" accept' 
     To permanently block an IP address: sudo firewall-cmd --permanent --add-rich-rule='rule family="ipv4" source address="192.168.1.200" reject'
